<subSubSection pageId="447" pageNumber="448" type="diversity">
<paragraph pageId="447" pageNumber="448">Diversity.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="447" pageNumber="448">
About 35 species in the Nearctic (11 species), Neotropical (seven species), Australian (one non-endemic species), Oriental (five species), Palaearctic (12 species, none in the Far East), and Afrotropical (seven species, three shared with Eurasia) Regions. One species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Blackburn" authorityYear="1878" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Tachys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="447" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="oahuensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="447" pageNumber="448">Tachys oahuensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Blackburn, is endemic to the Hawaiian Islands.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="447" pageNumber="448" type="identification">
<paragraph pageId="447" pageNumber="448">Identification.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="447" pageNumber="448">
Lindroth (1966: 427-431) treated five (one of them, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="LeConte" authorityYear="1852" class="Hexapoda" family="Carabidae" genus="Tachys" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Coleoptera" pageId="447" pageNumber="448" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="corax">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="447" pageNumber="448">Tachys corax</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in the key only) of the species found in North America and Hayward (1900: 218-224) eight species. A taxonomic revision of the species of this subgenus is needed.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
